<paragraph id="636036EAFFAD8542779EFE63FE77E1E2" blockId="56.[144,759,198,1290]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">
The MNHN apparently does not hold the type material of 
<taxonomicName id="A4DF4D69FFAD8542762EFE42FE43E036" authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[280,409,504,525]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD8542762EFE42FE43E036" box="[280,409,504,525]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">A. mitratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(C. Rollard, pers. comm.) and we consider it here lost. However, we accept Sherriffs’ (1918, 1919) concept of 
<taxonomicName id="A4DF4D69FFAD854276AAFD8FFDC7E070" authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[412,541,565,587]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD854276AAFD8FFDC7E070" box="[412,541,565,587]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">A. mitratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a species occurring in southern Indian mountain regions and redescribe the species here based on an examination of Sherriffs’ (1918, 1919) original material (ZMUC12902) and conspecific material from southern 
<collectingCountry id="1BC8767AFFAD854277A6FD74FF17E0DF" box="[144,205,718,740]" name="India" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">India</collectingCountry>
collected more recently by the senior author. In accordance with ICZN Article 75.3.1, we here designate a 
<typeStatus id="BC648848FFAD854277D8FCB6FE9DE11A" box="[238,327,780,801]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">neotype</typeStatus>
for 
<taxonomicName id="A4DF4D69FFAD854276B2FCB6FDDFE11A" authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[388,517,780,801]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD854276B2FCB6FDDFE11A" box="[388,517,780,801]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">A. mitratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to clarify the type locality of the species, which is doubtful based on the original description by 
<bibRefCitation id="074E4B1BFFAD854276AAFCF2FDB2E165" author="Simon E" box="[412,616,840,862]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" refId="ref37714" refString="Simon E. 1895. Histoire naturelle des araignees. Paris: Roret." type="book" year="1895">Simon (1895: 805</bibRefCitation>
: ‘montagnes de l’Inde’). This designation is also necessary to explicitly avoid confusion with 
<taxonomicName id="A4DF4D69FFAD85427525FC3CFD08E1A0" baseAuthorityName="Tikader" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[531,722,902,923]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="himalayaensis">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD85427525FC3CFD08E1A0" box="[531,722,902,923]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">P. himalayaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a congeneric species that is found in northern mountainous regions of 
<collectingCountry id="1BC8767AFFAD8542765FFC79FE73E1E2" box="[361,425,963,985]" name="India" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="636036EAFFAD8542779EFC58FECEE731" blockId="56.[144,759,198,1290]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">
We here propose the transfer of this species to 
<taxonomicName id="A4DF4D69FFAD854277A6FBBAFF16E62E" authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" box="[144,204,1024,1045]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD854277A6FBBAFF16E62E" box="[144,204,1024,1045]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Plebs</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A4DF4D69FFAD854277EAFBBBFDDBE62D" authority="(Simon, 1895)" authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[220,513,1024,1046]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD854277EAFBBBFE82E62D" box="[220,344,1025,1046]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">P. mitratus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="074E4B1BFFAD8542765FFBBAFE23E62D" author="Simon E" box="[361,505,1024,1046]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" refId="ref37714" refString="Simon E. 1895. Histoire naturelle des araignees. Paris: Roret." type="book" year="1895">Simon, 1895</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="4A985783FFAD8542753CFBBAFD5EE62E" box="[522,644,1024,1046]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, based on somatic and genitalic morphology, in particular the distinct ventral coloration of the abdomen with inverted light U-shaped pattern and additional spots anterolateral of the spinnerets (
<figureCitation id="FBE42A6FFFAD85427534FBC0FD5CE6AB" box="[514,646,1146,1168]" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="55.[164,243,1584,1603]" captionTargetBox="[327,1275,195,1553]" captionTargetId="figure-95@55.[323,1283,195,1554]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="Figure 34. Plebs mitratus comb. nov. A, B, female from Aana Mudi Shola National Park, India (WAM T109510). A, dorsal view; B, ventral view. C–F, female from Nilgiris, Tamil Nadu, India (ZMUC 12902). C, dorsal view; D, ventral view; E, epigyne, ventral view; F, epigyne, dorsal view). Scale bar = 2.0 mm in A-D; 0.5 mm in E; 0.2 mm in F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408791/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Fig. 34B, D</figureCitation>
) (synapomorphy of 
<taxonomicName id="A4DF4D69FFAD8542763CFB23FE9CE695" authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" box="[266,326,1177,1198]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD8542763CFB23FE9CE695" box="[266,326,1177,1198]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Plebs</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<figureCitation id="FBE42A6FFFAD85427663FB23FE4DE694" box="[341,407,1177,1199]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="12.[144,223,1760,1779]" captionTargetBox="[250,1316,199,1728]" captionTargetId="graphics-0@12.[250,1316,206,1728]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 3. Phylogenetic hypothesis for Plebs within a taxon sampling of Australian ‘eriophorine’ orb-weaving spiders (Araneidae) (length = 114, consistency index = 0.38, retention index = 0.72). Full circles indicate unambiguous synapomorphies and open circles homoplasious character state changes. Character numbers (above circles) and states (below circles) as in Table 1. The topology only shows unambiguous character state changes. Bremer support values are given in circles below branches." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408731/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). In contrast to all other Asian 
<taxonomicName id="A4DF4D69FFAD854277A6FB02FF16E6F6" authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" box="[144,204,1208,1229]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD854277A6FB02FF16E6F6" box="[144,204,1208,1229]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Plebs</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the species is redescribed here in detail as no illustrations or detailed descriptions are available for 
<taxonomicName id="A4DF4D69FFAD854277A6FB4FFED7E731" authorityName="Joseph &amp; Framenau" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="SIMON" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[144,269,1269,1290]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Plebs" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitratus">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD854277A6FB4FFED7E731" box="[144,269,1269,1290]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">P. mitratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="636036EAFFAD854277A6FA85FE39E76E" blockId="56.[144,483,1343,1365]" box="[144,483,1343,1365]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD854277A6FA85FEFBE76F" box="[144,289,1343,1364]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Distribution:</emphasis>
Southern 
<collectingCountry id="1BC8767AFFAD854276A9FA85FE05E76E" box="[415,479,1343,1365]" name="India" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="636036EAFFAD854277A6FA30FD95E4AE" blockId="56.[144,759,1418,1685]" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis id="51ABEAF8FFAD854277A6FA30FDE8E7A4" box="[144,562,1418,1439]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="335">Life history and habitat preferences:</emphasis>
Although adults have been observed throughout the year, the peak occurrence is from September to January. The spiders prefer a temperate climate and are generally restricted to higher altitudes (above 
<quantity id="A4279B0FFFAD8542757DF9BEFD78E421" box="[587,674,1540,1562]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="56" pageNumber="335" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000 m</quantity>
). Webs can generally be found in low grassy vegetation in open pockets of forests especially on the edges of forest trails. Webs are often decorated with stabilimentum (M. M. Joseph, pers. observ.).
</paragraph>
